english:
  title: A Record of Yangchon
  author: Lee Saek
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Yangchon is the literary name of my student Gwon Geun of Yeongga. Geun once told me: "I am young among my master's disciples, and my learning the lowest. Yet what I aspire toward is to journey from the near to the far. Thus I took the name 'Kayuan'—one who may reach far."

    In all things near and far: seeking within ourselves, we find sincerity; seeking without, we find the sun's warmth. Only the noble man can truly practice sincerity, yet the sun's warmth—even the simplest man and woman know it. Spring brings its gentle heat, summer its fierce brilliance, autumn its dry breath, winter gives way to warmth again. Thus the year's work is accomplished, and the people's lives unfold.

    Geun observed that how the sage develops human talent follows this same pattern. The teachings of Poetry, History, Rites, and Music all accord with Heaven's seasons. Confucius once said: "Do you think I hide myself? I hide nothing from you." Indeed, Confucius was like Heaven and Earth, like sun and moon—vast and all-encompassing, shining without shadow, illuminating all things. Within this light, every form, every color stands revealed without concealment. Thus it is written: the hawk soars to heaven, the fish leaps in the deep—showing how the Way penetrates above and below. What hiddenness could there be? Even those of twisted heart cannot escape this illumination. The Master's knowledge knows no bounds, his transformation reaches all things—bright as dawn, vast as the infinite ocean.

    Even those who bathed by the stream and felt the wind understood harmony flowing through all being, indistinguishable from the spirit of the ancient sage-kings Yao and Shun. What more need be said of how rain comes in season, how all things bloom and flourish?

    Alas, though Confucius was like Heaven and Earth, like sun and moon, among the three thousand who studied with him, even the seventy closest disciples rarely glimpsed this radiant Way. Yet Zengzi and Zisi were blessed to leave their words for us. Only when the teachings of Lianduo spread could scholars read their writings as if wandering Confucius's Heaven and Earth, as if gazing upon his sun and moon. Since Qin and Han, darkness has veiled the world, obscurity has reigned like a demon's spell—yet when the pure wind rises, it sweeps away without trace. How magnificent!

    October lacks the sun's warmth, yet we call it the month of Yang. This too is the sage's intention. In the teaching "do not eat the abundant fruit," we see how the sage preserves Yang to its utmost. The Spring and Autumn Annals are the sage's heart. The unicorn, a creature of Yang, was captured and grieved him deeply. Thus he wrote the Annals, beginning with "Spring, the royal first month"—which interpreters say means "the great unity of all under heaven."

    Oh, when a scholar lives in this age and meets his time, let him serve the Son of Heaven to establish this great unity, bringing the warmth of spring to all lands. As for me, I am old—what more can I hope for? Kayuan, hold fast to your chosen name and strengthen your resolve. How should you strengthen it? Begin always with sincerity.

    Written in the third month of spring in the year jiwei, on the day guiyou.
  footnotes:
    - Yangchon (陽村) literally means 'sun village' or 'warm village,' reflecting the philosophical importance of yang throughout this text.
    - Lianduo (濂洛) refers to the Neo-Confucian philosophers Zhou Dunyi (濂溪先生) and the Cheng brothers (洛陽諸賢), whose metaphysical system revived classical Confucian learning.
    - The phrase about the hawk and fish is from the I Ching (易經), suggesting the manifestation of the Way at all levels of existence.
    - Yao and Shun represent the sage-king model of virtue and good governance in Confucian tradition.
